segments.text: after this comment.
Okay.
I'm trying to find the details of how I brought this to the board.
Okay.
I told the board I'll make every effort I can to work with President Miller in an amicable situation.
I went to Jarvis and told him that.
I subsequently made a trip by air to every board member's location.
That was when I took to each of them this reorganization plan.
And it was at that time that I picked up the strong sentiment in the direction that I'm talking about.
I came back and was asked how I had come out in my efforts to work amicably, and I indicated that I didn't think it was working.
I was getting signals which I thought were authentic.
that in his staff meetings and on other occasions he would blast the chancellor's office openly, disparagingly, what's the word?
Disparagingly, I think.
That's what I came out with, but it didn't feel right, but in a negative way.
So they said, well, okay.
They called in separately to meet with them in executive session in my absence, Perry Atkinson and Fred Benson, to ask them if they thought this reorganization plan was workable.
I don't know how Perry reacted to it.
The strong agriculturalist in him, I think, he had some reservations about it.
I believe Benson supported it wholeheartedly, saying it probably was a good idea.
At any rate,
When I got back and went to the board, made the recommendation for.
No.
One member of the board.
Said we shouldn't leave this thing to Frank.
To take the entire onus of.
We've got to carry a part of the burden ourselves.
I hereby recommend that we terminate the services of President Miller.
Period.
It was seconded.
And I said, gentlemen, before you vote on this motion, let me make a comment, if you will.
Let's reassign this gentleman.
Let's not terminate him.
We have previously gotten ourselves into trouble by terminating a person, a tenured person.
I looked into the tenure.
I had earlier looked into the tenure of President Miller.
He was tenured, but the tenure never originated from the department, was not reviewed by the department.
I don't know how it could have happened, but apparently President Miller took it to the board for him to have tenure.
Or some board member offered it to the board.
I'm not sure.
But he was tenured.
And I told the board, let's not play the game again of getting ourselves in trouble over a tenure matter, if you will.
reassign him to the chancellor's office and I'll take care of it from there.
So they made that motion and it passed.
After that, we talked about a successor, an interim successor.
I was asked to name two or three people.
I named Harry Kunkel and Charles Sampson.
Charles Sampson, mainly because of my experience with him,
on the board of directors of the Bank of A&M.
I thought he was a good board member.
It was probably the weakest decision I ever made, Haskell.
It wasn't a good decision at all.
And I wasn't aware that it wouldn't be.
But when I named those two names, one board member said, well, we've had agriculturalists for some time.
Let's try an engineer.
So that's how Chuck got in on an interim basis.
And that was on a Wednesday afternoon?
I don't know.
It was a... Was this the same day that Jarvis was called over and told of the decision that he... No.
I don't think Jarvis was ever called over and given by the board advance notice that this was going to happen.
Oh, no, no, no.
But I was thinking of the day that he was told it had happened, that as of this point you are no longer the president.
No, no.
It happened right in his presence.
He was at the board meeting, and the board called him in after the executive session and said, President Miller, we are reassigning you.
Now, that happened on a Wednesday.

because you and I chatted in your office on Tuesday morning as I was saying goodbye, thank you for all that you've meant to me from the seventh grade through the 12th grade, and then as dean, and you asked me, because you really caught my attention, you said, who are the five best department heads on the campus, as I was ready to leave.
I said, huh?
And then you said, start with engineering.
And so I mentioned Charlie Holland.
And you said, well, what about Chuck Sampson?
And I said, well, he's not a department head.
You asked me why.
And I didn't want to tell you that a number of the senior faculty had gone to Benson to say, Chuck's really not leading us as well now as he was.
I didn't want to.

All right, I go back and I told Mac that, and I said, Mac, I think I know who the new vice chancellor for engineering at the system level might be, because we'd heard a rumor that there might be a vice chancellor for engineering and a vice chancellor for agriculture, Adkisson being one of them.
And that was on Tuesday, and then Jarvis is...
The decision is made on Wednesday...
And I hear about it that night in the wee hours in El Paso.
You want to quit for today?
Yeah, that's a good time.
Okay, we're checking to be sure that this is working.
Transcriber, this is, I believe, the 11th of May.
I mean, 11th of April, and when we transcribe it, we will just indicate that these interviews were done on three days.
Check yours, Dr. Hubert.
Okay, and this is the third day, and we're starting at about almost 10 o'clock.
Let's see, chronologically, when we quit, you were the chancellor.
We're into the 1980s, and...
Dr. Sampson served as the interim president for a year and then searched for a new A&M president.
Can you summarize that search and how the selection of Dr. Vandiver came about?
Yes, we advertised nationally, received a number of
applications, Vandiver was not one of them, and proceeded with the search in the customary fashion, narrowed it down to a few people and had interviews with them.
Really never did find the zinger that turned the board on
and the search committee.
The board had appointed a search committee also.
During the course of this search, the local newspaper, the Eagle, pushed and pushed for lists of candidates, the short list, and wanted to know all of the procedures that were going on and such.
The board had decided we would not release this information.
And I stood by that.
And as a consequence, I personally was challenged in the courts by the EGLE for not releasing the names of the applicants and the short list and so on.
And as you might know, the eagle prevailed.
The court ruled in favor of the eagle.
A&M, Mr. Hubert, you've got to release these names and release them now.
And, of course, we did in compliance with the court order.
We had also a...
a professional search firm out of Dallas who was giving us names of individuals.
And we really didn't get a lot of help from them.
They were more helpful later on in the search for a chancellor for my replacement when I retired.
But back to the course, the selection finally just almost came to a halt.
The board didn't really feel comfortable
strongly about any of the applicants or candidates.
Frank Vandiver came into the picture as a consequence of my suggesting his name as a potential candidate and another board member
I think it was John Blocker of Houston supporting it strongly.
And he was invited to submit his credentials.
He was then at North Texas State University as president.
He did submit his credentials.
The board had a meeting in Dallas
at which time we invited Mr. Vandiver to come down from Denton and spend several hours with us.
He did.
And as a result of that meeting, he was selected as president.
And that started the Vandiver years.
I think Vandiver's great accomplishments were
in the realm of improving faculty relationships with the administration and in removing A&M's name from the black list of the American Association of University Professors.
Frank, I think almost single-handedly in several trips to AAUP headquarters and visiting with them was able to
have A&M cleared of any problems with AAUP.
Now, what was the next part?
All right, and you and he worked together for about how long before your retirement?
Don't recall.
I don't recall that timeline.
You retired when?
I retired in July the 1st, 82.
What were, as you...
were approaching that date, what were your feelings about your career at A&M?
Oh, they were so strongly positive, Haskell.
I felt what a good fortune had fallen upon me when I came to A&M.
It was a moment in time where A&M was ready to move forward

And I was happy to be swept up into the momentum of that movement and all of the subsequent events and happenings that took place, the venture study, the aspiration study, the implementation of those studies, the reorganization of the university from a
four degree granting segments to what, now 10 or 11.
And simply the opportunity to be a part of that renaissance at Texas A&M was just absolutely exhilarating.
And surprisingly, to close out my A&M career after serving in three deanships, each for about a period of six years.
I was a dean total 20 years in three different colleges.
to have the opportunity to move into the chancellor's office and succeed Jack Williams, albeit there was an interim in between, was absolutely a thrilling capstone to the A&M career.
Some of the key people that you associated with, can you kind of describe their ability?
Tom Cherry.
Tom was very astute, outstanding, low profile, low key in his position, former experience in the business affairs of one of the major airlines.
I've forgotten which one it was now.
I want to say TWA.
But nonetheless, Tom brought a good stability to the president's office.
And I think...
was good for President Rudder.
Clyde Freeman.
Clyde is an exceptionally astute business and finance person.
I think he knew more about the permanent university fund and the available fund than anyone in our sector of the state.
He was...
He was a man filled with massive amounts of information, financial information.
Historically, he was, from the historical perspective of the financial affairs of the university and the system, he was without a peer.
He could recite
a decade ago, two decades ago, and give you time, place, date, who, where, when, how, and why, that kind of a fellow, a big help.
General Peel, the vice chancellor for physical facilities and construction,
had come to the university system two or three years prior to my coming on the scene there.
And he had a rich experience in the military.
He was a, I think, a major or lieutenant, I guess a major general with the engineering corps of the armed forces.

had handled massive construction projects before and was capable of working with a multi, multi-million dollar construction budget, overseeing everything that went on from the planning stages to the final completion.
Just an outstanding talent.
When you needed advice, to whom, I'm not going to ask you the negative, only the positive, to whom did you turn for advice and counsel first?
I think it would be Clyde Freeman Haskell that I would visit with.
He was always knowledgeable about board affairs and board matters.
And although he did not have the background in academics,
He had been associated with them sufficiently that he had a good insight into a proper course to follow, or questions to ask.
And he was helpful all along.
I would say particularly in budget matters and in preparation of materials for submission to the legislature.
Bob Cherry was exceedingly helpful in legislative matters.

Bob had earned the high respect of the people in Austin in the legislature as an adroit politician, lobbyist, spokesman for Texas A&M University and the system, and he was highly regarded by members of both the legislature and the Senate.
He was helpful in
reviewing the presentations I made to the various legislation hearing groups, the budget committees and so forth, and making suggestions for strengthening them.
And he was a good help.
When you went to Austin for court and board and or legislature, who were your key aides in those efforts?
Politicians and or staff?
I, Haskell, strangely enough, on those occasions, I traveled alone.
But did you have anyone that would be your ally, key ally in your... Well, Bob Cherry was there present all the time.
I felt that if I got into a ditch...
or into a quandary about some issue or some question that was directed at me, I could turn to Bob for help.
Clyde Freeman was usually along and I could get help from him.
Did we have a system person in Austin pretty permanently during the legislative session?
Not during my time, except during the latter years
The purchase of the old.
What's the name?
Oh, that house in Austin, the house in Austin.
Begins with an H. It was it was to be headquarters for a permanent residence in Austin.
Oh John Hutchison.
Was moved to Austin.
Bob asked for an assistant to help him with legislative matters.
During my term as chancellor, the board approved it, and during the session, John Hutchison would move to Austin and stay there on site.
He didn't stay annually.
He had come back at the close of the session, and he was a big help to Bob.
Which legislators were A&M's best allies?
Bill Moore, of course, in the Senate as chairman of the Finance Committee.
Bill
or anyone else who held that position could wield a lot of influence.
In the house, there was a chap from up in the plains of Texas.
I'm trying to remember his name.
who was such a strong supporter, and he had a good, long tenure as a House of Representatives member.
Not Heatley, was it?
No, no.
No.
I don't think Heatley was a great supporter of Texas A&M.
That's what I was going to be surprised.
No, Heatley was not friendly to us.
Because Dr. Williams used to call him S.O.B.
Heatley, Sweet Old Bill.
Heatley, I think, was from the Plains, too.
Paducah.
And he was essentially a Texas Tech man.
Oh, he wanted a college of veterinary medicine at Tech.
Now, let's see, some other key people that we want to be sure we touch on.
One is Lloyd Heaton, a kind of a campus leader forever.
Describe Lloyd Heaton and his characteristics.
I think it's unusual in an institution for the registrar of that institution to evolve to such a place of recognition that Lloyd Heaton held.
Lloyd was a kind, gentle, soft-spoken individual who was a member of all of the key committees.
President Rutter, and he may have had this spot before President Rutter, I don't know,
But at least with President Rutter, he was secretary of the executive committee.
He was a member of the academic council.
And Lloyd was, I think, important more for the information which he had and which he didn't talk about than for any other reason.
Lloyd kept the minutes for the executive committee, and I think possibly for the academic council, as I recall.
I don't remember so well the minutes of the academic council, but I do know that in the minutes for the executive committee, I was somewhat frustrated when I reviewed them at the end of a meeting
The minutes never revealed who made a motion or who seconded it and what the vote was.
It would simply indicate that a motion to do such and such was passed, period.
Well, that told the essence of the story.
But from the standpoint of building a history for an institution, it told very little about who did what and who supported and endorsed what.
That seemed to be typical of many records at A&M.
They didn't give the
They didn't give the details of the action taken and the background for it.
But Lloyd was the secretary of the academic council and the executive committee, and it was in that context that I knew him best.
Also, occasionally I'd have
I'd have cause to call upon him for help with some set of records or data and such.
He was always willing to supply them and in good time.
Transcriber, this is an editor's note that we will identify as editor's note.
I have heard the story that Lloyd Heaton has said a number of times, quote, over my dead body will we ever have black students at Texas A&M, period, end quote.
I also understand that just before the first black students enrolled, Mr. Rutter, having made that arrangement with great skill, called Mr. Heaton and told him to review the transcripts
to be sure that each of those students was enrolled in the appropriate course in the appropriate section and that he, Lloyd Heaton, was to call each instructor

of each of those sections to let them know that when they went to class the next day, there would be black students there, they had been duly admitted and enrolled, and that this was a call to be sure that there would be no problem and no misunderstanding.
And as a result of that, the enrollment and attendance of the first black students could not have gone more smoothly.
And Mr. Heaton carried out that assignment, as far as I recall, superbly.
His commanding officer, President Rutter, had given him a direction and he followed it.
End of note.
When you became, who were your key staff officers in the, who were your key staff in your office when you became chancellor?
When I became chancellor?
Who were the key office people?
You didn't take Peggy Ritchie with you, I don't think, did you?
No.
I didn't take Peggy with me, nor did I take Brian Cole with me.
And the reason was that in Peggy's case, twofold.
I knew that going to the chancellor's office was...
